    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1046208739" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1046208739" />
    <a title="Annie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24476089-annie"><img alt="Annie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1503503332p2/24476089.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1046208739?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Annie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Annie" href="/user/show/24476089-annie">Annie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099448563" href="/book/show/17256597-after-the-quake">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24476089-annie?shelf=read-in-2014">read-in-2014</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1046208739" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8450390695454766855">In true Murakami style, where the plot isn’t so much important but rather a green screen for the characters to perform. But something so surreal and fascinating, its like taking a dive into what you would think is azure water, only it is not.<br/><br/> The surrealism that forms the centrifugal force in his stories like The Wind Up Bird  Chronicle ,continues its trend in this collection of short stories, each a derivative of the seismic upheaval in Kobe. Each story dips into the troubled waters and emerges</span>
  <span id="freeText8450390695454766855" style="display:none">In true Murakami style, where the plot isn’t so much important but rather a green screen for the characters to perform. But something so surreal and fascinating, its like taking a dive into what you would think is azure water, only it is not.<br /><br /> The surrealism that forms the centrifugal force in his stories like The Wind Up Bird  Chronicle ,continues its trend in this collection of short stories, each a derivative of the seismic upheaval in Kobe. Each story dips into the troubled waters and emerges with a sense of being wrapped up in not so neat a bow, much is heartfelt much the same.<br /><br />What appeals most to me about ATQ, is the smoke and mirrors subjects and fascinating characters like a giant frog plotting to get rid of an evil underground giant worm or a bitter divorced lady landing up in an unknown lady’s home who tells her that she has a stone inside her. Unbelievable situations, inspired from real events, written in a comic style with an underlying Dosteovsky vibe- if you haven’t read this, do you really need more incentive?<br /><br />But do not be mistaken!, its not all fantasy, smeared elegantly in the stories with as unpretentious a tone as you can is the underlying note of realism: <br /><br />  “Earthquakes make people realise how fragile the ordinary world is” : a heart wrenching plunge into the dark reality of the disaster and the sarin gas attacks that forced Murakami himself to uproot his life to a foreign land, it veers the narrative ever so slightly into the dissection of the emotional state by the horror of these events. So the stone inside the women’s body is not just a stone, and the subterrarian worm is not just. <br /><br />Weird, plain, fascinating and Haruki Murakami at his best. A perfect introduction to classic Murakami, or just a perfect read anytime!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8450390695454766855" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1046208739">
