<div id="review_2375689493" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2375689493" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2375689493?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2375689493" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1500884297029604003">Murukami’s stories are ripe for pastiche and parody; ridden with tropes and characters which exist solely in Murukami’s stories, but which constantly pop-up; lackadaisical loners, tortured artists, the disaffected and the deranged, talking animals, convoluted plots; they can, if read concurrently, grate on the reader, but, taken in small doses, they emphasise the magic of Murukami’s imagination, resplendent with the weird and wonderful workings of his mind, a testament to his unrivalled storytel</span>
  <span id="freeText1500884297029604003" style="display:none">Murukami’s stories are ripe for pastiche and parody; ridden with tropes and characters which exist solely in Murukami’s stories, but which constantly pop-up; lackadaisical loners, tortured artists, the disaffected and the deranged, talking animals, convoluted plots; they can, if read concurrently, grate on the reader, but, taken in small doses, they emphasise the magic of Murukami’s imagination, resplendent with the weird and wonderful workings of his mind, a testament to his unrivalled storytelling abilities.<br /><br />My favourite story in this collection is ‘Super Frog Saves Tokyo’, in which an erudite giant frog who, when not quoting Dostoevskii and Nietschze is planning to fight a giant worm who is threatening to destroy Tokyo in the manner that Anna Karenina fought a train. All of this is told via the eyes of a rather diffident debt collector who may, or may not, have imagined the whole thing. Yet the wonder of being caught up in this dream, in Katagiri’s frog-man fantasies, is what matters-after all fiction is make believe and whether Katagiri made up super-frog or not is irrelevant. What matter is the storyteller’s ability to capture and captivate the reader and Murukami is perhaps at his best when he gives free reign to his imagination.<br /><br />The other stories are dominated by the characters who typically populate a Murukami novel, the waifs and strays, the losers and loners who occupy the worlds he creates, whether it is the fridgophobe Miyake in ‘Landscape with Flirtation’ or the lachrymose writer Junpei in ‘Honey Pie’, Murukami explores the varying reasons for their isolation; it is usually wrapped in feelings of loss, whether it be romantic rejection or the break-down of a friendship, Murukami is able to sensitively navigate the feelings and histories of the characters whose lives have lead them down a path of solitude and seclusion; a paean to pathos, Murukami’s stories subtly explores the different and individual ways to be human and deal with pain and loss</span>
  <a data-text-id="1500884297029604003" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


