<div id="review_31212006" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/31212006" />
    <a title="Matthew Snope" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/142384-matthew-snope"><img alt="Matthew Snope" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1263251534p2/142384.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/31212006?book_show_action=true">Aug 26, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Snope" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Snope" href="/user/show/142384-matthew-snope">Matthew Snope</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer31212006" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11119527636562426254">This is worth getting your grubby hands on just for the amazing short story &quot;landscape with flatiron&quot;. For fuck&apos;s sake this guy can write. Sometimes some of his stuff is more appealing to me than others, but I&apos;m blown away overall at his talent and prolificness. I&apos;m also finding myself more drawn to shorter stories lately, having less patience for the modern grand master narrative of the epic novel, preferring instead the more fragmented, shorter, leaner &amp; meaner postmodern narrative in the form</span>
  <span id="freeText11119527636562426254" style="display:none">This is worth getting your grubby hands on just for the amazing short story "landscape with flatiron". For fuck's sake this guy can write. Sometimes some of his stuff is more appealing to me than others, but I'm blown away overall at his talent and prolificness. I'm also finding myself more drawn to shorter stories lately, having less patience for the modern grand master narrative of the epic novel, preferring instead the more fragmented, shorter, leaner &amp; meaner postmodern narrative in the form of the short story. Again, "landscape with flatiron", the second short story in this collection, is an instant classic, one of the best short stories I done ever read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11119527636562426254" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


